protocol.endpoint: Biodegradation in water: screening tests, IUC4#8/Ch.3.5

interpretation.criteria:
RS-Freetext:
Background study: examined effects of aeration on DMSO evaporation for  the experiment performed in flask cultures and air-lift bioreactor.

DMSO concentration in shake-flask solution aereted at a flow rate of 0.5  L/h was monitored for 70h and varied little for the initial concentration  of 100 and 900 mg DMSO/L: 97.02 +/- 3.06 mg DMSO/L and 901.27 +/- 1.80 mg  DMSO/L respectively.

DMSO concentrations in the air-lift bioreactor aereted at a flow rate of  10 L/min showed no statistical changes for the initial concentration of  700 mg DMSO/L.

Optimal temperature with the shorstest time (35h) achieved for  degradation of 250 mg DMSO/L at pH 6.8 was 30�C. At temperatures of 20,  25 and 35�C, complete degradation of DMSO required 80, 44 and 80h  respectively.

An optimum range of pH of 7.0-8.5 has been determined for DMSO  degradation.

Time needed for 500 mg/L DMSO biodegradation could be reduced to 16h at  the rate of 0.153 g DMSO per gram suspended solids per day if a repeated  batch mode was adopted, indicating that an acclimatation period is  required.

RS-Freetext:
Under the optimal conditions of pH 7.0-8.5 and 30 �C, the highest removal  efficiency in treatment of 500 mg/L of DMSO occurred at the rate of 0.078  g DMSO per gram suspended solids per day corresponding to 37 h for  complete DMSO biodegradation in a shake-flask culture.
However, the time needed for DMSO biodegradation could be reduced to 16 h  at the rate of 0.153 g DMSO per gram suspended solids per day if a  repeated-batch mode was adopted, indicating that an acclimation period is  required by the DMSO degraders. The reaction time could further be  shortened to less than 10 h with 95% removal of the 750 mg/L DMSO at the  maximum rate of 0.909 g DMSO per gram suspended solids per day using an  oxygen-enriched air-lift bioreactor.

Degradation products: no
